        "text": "Risk Mitigation and Alternative Approaches I recognize membrane protein structural biology's inherent unpredictability. If full-length EphA2 proves intractable, I'll pursue systematic domain combinations (kinase+transmembrane, then add SAM) to identify minimal constructs capturing oligomerization interfaces. If cryoEM resolution stalls above 4\u00c5, I'll pivot to capturing larger conformational changes that remain informative at lower resolution. Even 6\u00c5 structures showing domain rearrangements would advance the field. Should specific phosphomutants fail to stabilize distinct states, I'll screen small molecules known to bias EphA2 signaling as conformational tools. If planned internships don't materialize, I'll pursue extended collaborations with Eli Lilly (Indianapolis, 60 miles away) enabling regular visits while maintaining dissertation progress. These contingencies ensure productive training regardless of technical challenges. Transition to Next Career Stage This comprehensive training will prepare me for senior scientist positions in pharmaceutical structural biology. The combination of membrane protein expertise, cryoEM proficiency, and drug discovery experience will match current industry needs. My publications will demonstrate both technical excellence and translational applications and will establish credibility. The internship will provide networking and cultural understanding crucial for successful integration into industry. Additionally, my non-traditional background adds valuable perspective on persistence, resource optimization, and creative problem-solving. Research Environment Suitability Purdue provides ideal training through world-class facilities, collaborative culture, and strong industry connections. The cryoEM facility's Titan Krios will enable cutting-edge structural studies. Integration with drug discovery cores will facilitate translational applications. Dr. Stauffacher's mentorship record, with former students in lead