ons near regulatory regions. Using MEME for motif discovery and ClustalW for alignment optimization, I learned to identify patterns invisible to cursory analysis. This training proves essential now as I design EphA2 constructs, ensuring my truncations preserve functional motifs while removing disordered regions that impede crystallization. When I discovered certain EphA2 mutations cluster in regions controlling oligomerization rather than kinase activity, my training allowed me to recognize this as evidence of selection pressure, cancer cells specifically targeting regulatory mechanisms. At Argonne National Laboratory with Dr. Uisung Lee, I conducted comprehensive life-cycle analysis of polylactic acid, tracking energy and material flows across 50+ interconnected variables.  I had to understand how upstream changes propagated through the entire system, optimize multiple parameters simultaneously, and validate my model against real-world data. My work, now incorporated into the GREET\u00ae 2019 model used by researchers worldwide, required the same systematic thinking I apply to membrane protein purification. When optimizing EphA2 expression, I similarly track how changes in induction temperature affect not just yield but also protein folding, post-translational modifications, and ultimately structural homogeneity. This systems-level perspective helped me recognize that EphA2's tendency to aggregate wasn't a simple concentration effect but resulted from specific lipid depletion during purification, a connection I might have missed without my environmental analysis background. Molecular Biology and Technical Innovation My Master's research on Tonneau1 Recruiting Motif (TRM) proteins under Dr. Viktor Kirik provided essential molecular biology training. Using live-cell confocal microscopy, I tracked fluorescently-tagged TRM18 in plant cells, systematically creating deletion constructs to map functional domains through phenotypic analysis. This work taught me how removing or altering specific protein regions affects cellular localization and function. This is directly relevant to designing EphA2 constructs that maintain native behavior while being amenable to structural studies. My improvement to Gateway cloning (a method for moving DNA between plasmids), published in BioTechniques, streamlined the creation of these numerous constructs. By developing polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-based approaches that joined DNA fragments without expensive enzymes, I reduced costs by 70% while increasing cloning success rates. This same systematic approach to optimization now drives my membrane protein work. Current Specialization in Membrane Protein Structural Biology In Dr. Stauffacher's lab, I've transitioned from broad molecular biology to focused structural approaches. Initial attempts to crystallize EphA2's kinase domain taught me valuable lessons about construct design, protein stability, and the importance of post-translational modifications. When crystals diffracting to only 8\u00c5 revealed aggregation issues, I didn't simply try more conditions, I stepped back to understand why this well-behaved domain in solution became problematic in crystals. This led to my current approach using full-length protein in nanodiscs, preserving native oligomerization interfaces. My technical preparation now includes advanced coursework in macromolecular crystallography, where I learned to optimize crystallization strategies for challenging targets; biophysical methods, providing quantitative frameworks for validating protein functionality; and currently, comprehensive cryoEM training on Purdue's Titan Krios. I've spent countless hours studying grid optimization, learning that success requires understanding not just the microscope but also how proteins behave at air-water interfaces. Through the Purdue cryoEM facility, I'm gaining hands-on experience with every step from sample prep through data processing in RELION and cryoSPARC. This combination of computational pattern recognition, systematic optimization, and molecular biology creates a unique lens for approaching membrane protein challenges. Where traditional structural biologists might focus solely on crystallization conditions, my bioinformatics training alerts me to conserved motifs that must be preserved in constructs. My systems-level thinking from environmental modeling helps me recognize how seemingly unrelated variables (temperature, lipid composition, buffer pH) interact to affect protein stability. The iterative optimization skills honed through Gateway cloning improvements transfer directly to the patient, methodical screening required for membrane protein success. Most importantly, my cross-disciplinary path taught me that breakthroughs often come from applying insights from unexpected sources. This convergence of skills from multiple fields positions me to see solutions that single-discipline training might miss. Candidate's Self-Assessment Current Strengths Systems-Level Thinking My diverse research background enables me to recognize how interconnected variables affect protein behavior, from understanding transposon evolution patterns to optimizing multi-parameter environmental models, I approach EphA2 as a complex system rather than isolated technical challenges. Technical Innovation I consistently identify and improve inefficient processes, evidenced by my Gateway cloning optimization (70% cost reduction) and recognizing that full-length EphA2 in nanodiscs could succeed where isolated domain crystallization failed. Cross-Disciplinary Pattern Recognition Years of jumping between fields trained me to apply insights from unexpected sources, like using environmental chemistry principles to solve membrane protein lipid requirements. Areas for Development Advanced CryoEM Data Processing I aim to build expertise in particle classification and conformational heterogeneity analysis by attending advanced cryoEM workshops at leading centers such as SEMC at Scripps or the Rutgers CryoEM/ET Core. Quantitative Biophysics I will strengthen my ability to design and interpret ITC and SPR experiments through hands-on training with our core facility, essential for proving that different EphA2 conformations represent functionally distinct signaling states rather than crystallization artifacts. High-Impact Scientific Writing I will develop skills in crafting compelling scientific narratives through the Purdue Writing Lab's advanced workshops, learning to contextualize structural discoveries within broader therapeutic implications, crucial for industry where data must justify investment decisions. Scientific Communication While I write clearly for specialists, I need to develop skills in translating complex structural findings for diverse audiences, from computational chemists to clinical researchers to business executives. This gap could limit my effectiveness in pharmaceutical settings where I must justify research directions to non-structural biologists. Scientific Perspective RTKs represent the largest oncogene family, yet we lack structural information for effective therapeutics. This gap has profound consequences, RTK drugs generate billions but inevitably fail, leaving patients without options. We've been designing drugs blind, without seeing how multi-domain proteins function as integrated membrane machines. EphA2 exemplifies this challenge. Overexpressed in 40% of breast cancers and 90% of glioblastomas, EphA2 paradoxically suppresses tumors when ephrin-bound but drives metastasis when protein kinase B (AKT)-phosphorylated. Cancer cells exploit this conformational flexibility, turning a regulatory protein into a progression engine. Current drugs miss the allosteric mechanisms controlling whether EphA2 helps or harms. My research aims to capture atomic-resolution views of full-length EphA2 transitioning between tumor-suppressive and oncogenic states. By maintaining membrane environments throughout structural studies, I