            "Specific Aims Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) regulate cell communication, development, and disease, yet the structural mechanisms by which extracellular ligand binding is transduced into intracellular signaling remain incompletely understood. EphA2, a member of the Eph family of RTKs, is overexpressed in many cancers and contributes to tumor progression, metastasis, and therapy resistance. Unlike many RTKs, EphA2 signals through both ligand-dependent and ligand-independent modes with distinct downstream consequences. A key effector is the guanine nucleotide exchange factor Vav2, whose recruitment depends on EphA2 activation. However, how ligand binding reshapes EphA2 conformation to regulate juxtamembrane phosphorylation and Vav2 engagement remains unknown. This gap limits our understanding of how RTK architecture governs signaling specificity, a central goal of the NIH mission. The long-term goal of my research is to define how full-length RTKs transduce ligand binding into spatially precise phosphorylation and effector recruitment. The objective of this proposal is to determine how ligand-induced conformational changes in EphA2 regulate juxtamembrane phosphostates and Vav2 activation. The rationale is that structural transitions in EphA2, particularly within the juxtamembrane region, control phosphosite accessibility and downstream signaling. My central hypothesis is that ligand binding induces a conformational shift in EphA2 that repositions the juxtamembrane regions, enabling phosphorylation and Vav2 recruitment. To test this hypothesis, I will define EphA2\u2019s ligand-induced structural transitions and determine how these conformational and phosphostate changes regulate Vav2 engagement. Aim 1: Determine the structure of full-length EphA2 in a near-native membrane environment to define juxtamembrane positioning and oligomer geometry in apo and ligand-bound states. Rationale: Structural understanding of ligand-induced EphA2 activation requires full-length receptor architectures that include transmembrane and membrane-proximal constraints. CryoEM of EphA2 reconstituted in nanodiscs will reveal how ligand binding alters oligomer geometry, juxtamembrane positioning, and phosphosite accessibility, providing a structural basis for ligand-dependent versus ligand-independent signaling. Approach: Full-length human EphA2 will be expressed, purified, and reconstituted into nanodiscs with defined lipid compositions. Sample quality will be assessed by SEC-MALS, ligand-binding assays, and autophosphorylation assays. Oligomeric states will be enriched by varying receptor:scaffold ratios, lipid composition, and ligand conditions and monitored by negative-stain EM. CryoEM structures will be determined to resolve juxtamembrane positioning and oligomeric interfaces at near-atomic resolution. Aim 2: Define how EphA2 conformation and juxtamembrane phosphostates regulate Vav2 recruitment and activation. Rationale: Although Vav2 recruitment depends on EphA2 phosphorylation, the molecular basis of this interaction is unknown. It remains unclear which juxtamembrane phosphotyrosines are recognized, whether Vav2 engages one or both sites, and how receptor oligomerization influences binding. An integrated biophysical approach is required to link EphA2 conformational states to effector engagement. Approach: Interactions between the Vav2 SH2 domain and EphA2 juxtamembrane phosphopeptides will be characterized using a hierarchical biophysical pipeline. ITC will quantify binding affinities and stoichiometries for single- and dual-phosphorylated peptides. Solution NMR will map binding interfaces and conformational changes upon engagement. Crystallographic structures of Vav2-SH2 bound to preferred phosphopeptides will define atomic-level binding geometry. These data will be integrated with Aim 1 structures to model how EphA2 oligomer geometry controls Vav2 accessibility and stoichiometry in the full-length receptor context. This project integrates strutural studies of full-length EphA2 with phosphorylation-defined biophysical studies to link receptor architecture to effector recruitment. The results will establish a mechanistic framework for EphA2 signaling specificity and inform strategies to modulate RTK signaling in cancer. RESEARCH STRATEGY Significance EphA2 is a receptor tyrosine kinase (RTK) whose signaling behavior defies the canonical ligandon/ligandoff paradigm that underlies most RTK models. In normal epithelial tissues, ephrin ligand engagement of EphA2 promotes receptor tyrosine phosphorylation and tumorsuppressive signaling pathways that limit cell migration and proliferation. In contrast, in many cancers where ephrin expression is reduced, mislocalized, or spatially uncoupled from EphA2, the receptor signals in a ligandindependent manner through serine phosphorylation, driving epithelial <span style=font-family:Symbol>&#x00AE;</span> mesenchymal transition, cytoskeletal remodeling, and metastatic behavior. This duality, tumor suppressor when ligandbound/oncogenic when ligandfree, implies that EphA2 adopts distinct conformational and organizational states that encode opposing biological outcomes. Despite extensive biochemical, genetic, and cellbased characterization of EphA2 signaling, the molecular basis of this switch remains unresolved. Numerous studies have identified key phosphorylation sites, interacting partners, and downstream pathways associated with EphA2 activity. However, these data have not converged on a mechanistic model explaining how extracellular ligand binding is physically coupled across the membrane to intracellular phosphorylation patterns and effector recruitment. Structures of isolated EphA2 domains, including the ligandbinding domain and kinase domain, have provided valuable snapshots of individual components but cannot explain how these domains are spatially coordinated in the intact receptor. In particular, the juxtamembrane (JM) region of EphA2 contains critical regulatory tyrosines required for downstream signaling, yet its positioning relative to the kinase domain and its accessibility in different receptor assemblies are unknown. Without structural information for the full-length receptor in a membrane context, current models of EphA2 regulation remain speculative. EphA2 is uniquely well suited as a model system for addressing this gap. Unlike many RTKs that signal primarily as ligandinduced dimers, Eph receptors form higherorder assemblies whose geometry influences signaling output. Ligand clustering, receptor density, and oligomer size have all been shown to modulate Eph signaling, suggesting that receptor organization itself is a regulatory variable. EphA2 also contains a Cterminal sterile alpha motif (SAM) domain that regulates receptor oligomerization, providing an additional layer of structural control absent from most RTKs. Together, these features make EphA2 an experimentally tractable system for interrogating how oligomeric organization, membrane embedding, and JM positioning cooperate to regulate RTK signaling. Importantly, the questions posed by EphA2 extend beyond this single receptor. The challenge of understanding how extracellular ligand binding is integrated with membrane organization and intracellular phosphorylation is shared across the RTK superfamily. EphA2 provides a particularly clear window into this problem because its signaling outputs are sharply bifurcated and biologically well defined. Insights gained from EphA2 are therefore expected to generalize beyond a single receptor, informing fundamental principles of RTK regulation across diverse signaling contexts. Understanding how fulllength EphA2 integrates ligand binding, membrane organization, and intracellular phosphorylation is directly relevant to cancer biology, as EphA2 dysregulation occurs across multiple tumor types, including breast cancer, glioblastoma, melanoma, and prostate cancer. However, the primary significance of this work lies in defining the structural logic by which RTKs function as integrated membrane assemblies. By resolving how EphA2 architecture changes between functional states, this project addresses a foundational problem in signal transduction that cannot be solved solely through biochemical or cellular approaches alone. Innovation This project is innovative in its conceptual framing, technical approach, and integrative strategy. Conceptually, it treats EphA2 not as a collection of independently regulated domains but as a dynamic, multidomain membrane assembly whose signaling output is encoded by its overall architecture. Rather than focusing solely on kinase activation or individual phosphorylation events, the proposed work explicitly interrogates how oligomer geometry and juxtamembrane positioning regulate phosphorylation accessibility and effector recruitment. This shifts the emphasis from local activesite regulation to global receptor organization as a determinant of signaling specificity. Technically, the project applies cryoelectron microscopy (cryoEM) to fulllength EphA2 reconstituted in lipid nanodiscs, preserving native transmembrane constraints and lipid interactions that are absent from detergentsolubilized or truncated constructs. Nanodiscs provide a defined yet flexible membrane environment that allows systematic manipulation of lipid composition while maintaining receptor integrity. The use of clustered ephrin ligands to bias receptor assembly states, combined with controlled variation of nanodisc composition and receptor density, enables exploration of biologically relevant oligomeric architectures that cannot be accessed using isolated domains or soluble constructs. These approaches leverage recent advances in membrane protein cryoEM to address questions that were previously inaccessible. Integratively, the project directly links structural states of the fulllength receptor to phosphorylationdependent effector engagement. By combining cryoEM with quantitative biophysical characterization of Vav2 recruitment to defined EphA2 JM phosphostates, the work connects architecture to mechanism. This structuretofunction integration moves beyond descriptive structural biology to establish how specific conformations encode signaling outcomes, providing a mechanistic framework for interpreting EphA2 signaling behavior. Approach Overall Strategy and Feasibility The overarching goal of this project is to define how ligandinduced conformational changes in fulllength EphA2 regulate juxtamembrane accessibility and downstream effector recruitment, thereby establishing a structural framework for understanding how this receptor toggles between distinct signaling outputs. Rather than treating EphA2 activation as a binary on-off process, this work approaches the receptor as a dynamic membrane assembly whose architecture encodes signaling competence. By focusing on fulllength EphA2 in a membrane context, the project is designed to capture spatial relationships among extracellular, transmembrane, and intracellular elements that cannot be inferred from isolated domains or biochemical readouts alone. The work is currently in an early execution phase, with construct generation for fulllength EphA2 and development of quantitative biophysical assays for Vav2 recruitment underway. This timing is well suited to a fellowship project that emphasizes mechanistic discovery and technical training, as it allows systematic optimization to be integrated directly into the experimental plan rather than treated as a secondary step. Feasibility is supported by wellestablished foundations. Baculovirus/Sf9 expression systems have been widely used to produce intact RTKs with appropriate folding and posttranslational modifications, lipid nanodiscs provide a robust and increasingly standard platform for reconstituting singlepass membrane proteins under defined conditions, and SH2-phosphopeptide interactions are amenable to rigorous quantitative analysis using complementary biophysical techniques. A central feature of the experimental strategy is its emphasis on systematic exploration rather than singleendpoint success. For Aim\u202f1, this involves treating ligand valency, receptor density, and membrane composition as biologically meaningful variables that shape EphA2 organization, rather than preselecting a single oligomeric state. For Aim\u202f2, it involves quantitatively dissecting how individual and combined juxtamembrane phosphorylation events tune effector recruitment, rather than assuming a simple threshold model. Across both aims, outcomes are intentionally tiered so that early stages yield interpretable information about receptor behavior and binding energetics even if higherresolution structural goals require additional optimization. Aim 1: Determine the structure of fulllength EphA2 in a nearnative membrane environment Rationale The central unresolved question in EphA2 signaling is how extracellular ligand binding reorganizes the fulllength receptor to control intracellular phosphorylation. While extensive biochemical and cellular studies have identified key regulatory phosphorylation sites and downstream effectors, these approaches cannot explain how ligand engagement on the extracellular surface is physically coupled across the membrane to changes in kinase activity and juxtamembrane accessibility. This limitation arises because EphA2 signaling is inherently spatial. The relative positioning of the ligandbinding domain, transmembrane helix, juxtamembrane (JM) region, kinase domain, and SAM domain determines which phosphorylation sites are exposed, which interfaces are stabilized, and which effectors can be recruited. Structures of isolated EphA2 domains have provided important insights into local interactions but cannot capture these longrange relationships. In particular, the JM region, containing the key regulatory tyrosines Y588 and Y594, has never been visualized in the context of the intact receptor. As a result, it remains unclear whether ligand binding alters JM accessibility by repositioning the kinase domains, by changing oligomer geometry, or by stabilizing specific receptor assemblies. Addressing these questions requires structural information of the fulllength receptor embedded in a membrane environment that preserves native transmembrane constraints and lipid interactions. Cryoelectron microscopy (cryoEM) of fulllength EphA2 reconstituted into lipid nanodiscs provides a direct means to visualize receptor architecture under nearnative conditions. Nanodiscs allow precise control over membrane composition while maintaining a defined lipid bilayer, enabling systematic interrogation of how ligand binding and membrane content influence EphA2 organization. By comparing apo and ligandbound states, this aim will establish how extracellular ligand engagement reshapes the fulllength receptor to regulate intracellular signaling competence. Experimental Design Fulllength human EphA2 will be expressed using a baculovirus/Sf9 system with affinity tags to facilitate purification. This expression system is well suited for large, multidomain membrane proteins and supports proper folding and posttranslational modification. Initial constructs will retain all domains without truncation to preserve native regulatory interactions, including the SAM domain and full JM region. Mutations or construct modifications will be introduced only if required to improve stability or homogeneity, and any such changes will be guided by biochemical behavior rather than preconceived structural assumptions. Purified EphA2 will be reconstituted into lipid nanodiscs using defined membrane scaffold proteins and lipid mixtures selected to support receptor stability and activity. Nanodisc composition will initially reflect common eukaryotic membrane lipids and will be adjusted as needed to optimize receptor behavior. Ligandfree samples will be compared to samples incubated with clustered ephrinA1 or ephrinA1Fc, which provide multivalent ligand engagement and more closely mimic physiological ephrin presentation. These ligand formats are expected to promote receptor assembly and stabilize signalingrelevant oligomeric states. Rather than targeting a single predefined oligomeric state, EphA2 organization will be explored as a function of biologically meaningful variables. Oligomeric state will be modulated through controlled variation of ligand valency, receptortoscaffold ratios during nanodisc assembly, and lipid composition. This strategy reflects the known sensitivity of Eph signaling to receptor density and ligand clustering and allows systematic mapping of how these parameters influence receptor architecture. Sample quality and assembly behavior will be assessed by sizeexclusion chromatography and negativestain EM prior to cryoEM data collection, enabling rapid identification of conditions that yield monodisperse, wellbehaved particles. CryoEM datasets will be collected for conditions that meet predefined quality criteria. Image processing will emphasize particle classification to resolve distinct assembly states, followed by threedimensional reconstruction of representative conformations. This approach is well suited to capturing the structural heterogeneity expected for a dynamic membrane receptor and allows separation of coexisting states rather than forcing a single averaged structure. Data Analysis and Interpretation Reconstructed maps will be analyzed to define overall domain organization and to identify changes in interdomain geometry associated with ligand engagement. Attention will be paid to the relative positioning of the JM region and kinase domains, as these relationships are expected to directly influence phosphorylation accessibility. Even at moderate resolution, differences in domain arrangement, oligomer geometry, and kinase proximity are expected to be mechanistically informative. Where resolution permits, atomic modeling will be used to define JM-kinase relationships and oligomer interfaces in greater detail. Comparisons between apo and ligandbound reconstructions will reveal how ligand binding biases EphA2 toward specific architectural states. These structural observations will generate testable hypotheses regarding how receptor organization controls downstream signaling, which will be directly addressed in Aim\u202f2. Potential Pitfalls and Alternative Strategies Low expression levels or sample heterogeneity may limit initial cryoEM data quality. In this case, construct optimization, tag repositioning, or modest sequence modifications will be pursued to improve behavior while preserving regulatory elements. If conformational heterogeneity precludes highresolution reconstruction, analysis will focus on lowerresolution domain rearrangements and oligomeric architectures, which remain highly informative for understanding signaling mechanisms. If enrichment of specific oligomeric states proves challenging, additional ligand clustering strategies or alternative lipid compositions will be explored to bias receptor organization. Each contingency preserves the ability to extract meaningful architectural insight from the system. Expected Outcomes This aim is expected to yield structural models of fulllength EphA2 that reveal how ligand binding reorganizes the receptor within the membrane. These models will define the spatial context of the JM region relative to the kinase domains and establish a structural framework for interpreting phosphorylationdependent signaling. By resolving how receptor architecture differs between functional states, Aim\u202f1 will provide the foundation for mechanistically linking EphA2 structure to downstream effector recruitment in Aim\u202f2. Aim 2: Define how EphA2 juxtamembrane phosphostates regulate Vav2 recruitment Rationale Genetic and biochemical studies indicate that phosphorylation of specific EphA2 juxtamembrane (JM) tyrosines is required for recruitment of the guanine nucleotide exchange factor Vav2, a key effector in EphA2-mediated cytoskeletal remodeling. However, the field still lacks a quantitative, residue-resolved description of how individual JM phosphosites, and their combinations, encode effector engagement. This aim treats the JM region as an information-bearing regulatory element rather than a passive linker. The working premise is that phosphorylation at Y588 and Y594 does not simply \u201cturn on\u201d binding, but tunes affinity, stoichiometry, and potentially binding mode in ways that can be mapped onto the structural states from Aim 1. In other words, Aim 2 provides the mechanistic decoder ring for interpreting what the architectures in Aim 1 mean for signaling output. Experimental design To define how EphA2 JM phosphorylation patterns regulate Vav2 recruitment, this aim will combine quantitative binding measurements with residuelevel structural mapping. A focused panel of synthetic JM peptides spanning the EphA2 segment containing Y588 and Y594 will be generated in four defined phosphorylation states: unphosphorylated, singly phosphorylated at Y588, singly phosphorylated at Y594, and doubly phosphorylated at both sites. Peptide lengths will be chosen to include flanking residues known to contribute to SH2 domain specificity, minimizing truncation artifacts while maintaining experimental tractability. In parallel, the Vav2 SH2 domain will be expressed and purified as a soluble recombinant protein, with alternative tag placements and buffer optimization employed if needed to preserve monodispersity without perturbing binding behavior. Quantitative characterization of Vav2 recruitment will be performed primarily using isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC). For each JM phosphostate, ITC will provide equilibrium dissociation constants, binding stoichiometries, and thermodynamic signatures, including enthalpic and entropic contributions. The unphosphorylated peptide will establish a baseline for nonspecific interactions and heatofdilution effects, while the singly phosphorylated peptides will test whether one JM tyrosine dominates recruitment or whether both contribute meaningfully. The doubly phosphorylated peptide will probe cooperativity, revealing whether the second phosphorylation event produces an affinity enhancement beyond simple additivity. Interpretation will extend beyond affinity ranking to analysis of thermodynamic signatures, as differences in enthalpy vs entropydriven binding can indicate distinct engagement modes and guide subsequent structural analysis. Because SH2-phosphopeptide interactions can be sensitive to assay format, ITCderived trends will be validated using at least one orthogonal method. Surface plasmon resonance or biolayer interferometry will be used to confirm affinity ordering and assess kinetic contributions, including association and dissociation rates not accessible by ITC. Immobilization strategies will be selected to minimize avidity artifacts and preserve a 1:1 binding regime. In addition, differential scanning fluorimetry will be used as a rapid screening tool to assess whether specific phosphopeptides stabilize the SH2 domain in a manner consistent with productive binding, enabling efficient prioritization of conditions for higherresolution studies. Residuelevel mapping of the Vav2-JM interaction will be carried out using solution NMR spectroscopy. Each phosphopeptide will be titrated into isotopically labeled Vav2 SH2 domain, and chemical shift perturbations will be monitored to define the binding interface and detect phosphostatedependent differences. NMR will distinguish whether all phosphostates engage a conserved SH2 binding surface or whether alternative geometries are sampled and will report on binding dynamics through exchange broadening or lineshape changes. These dynamic features will be particularly informative if Aim\u202f1 reveals heterogeneous EphA2 assemblies, as they may indicate conformational selection or multiple bound states. Where feasible, crystallization of Vav2 SH2-phosphopeptide complexes will be pursued to obtain atomiclevel interaction geometries. Phosphostates that exhibit the tightest, most wellbehaved binding in ITC and the most interpretable NMR perturbation patterns will be prioritized. Peptide length and terminal modifications will be treated as tunable variables to improve crystal packing without altering the core recognition motif. Even if crystallization proves intractable, negative results will still inform the project by narrowing plausible binding modes and focusing integration efforts on experimentally supported constraints rather than speculative models. Expected outcomes This aim is expected to yield a ranked and thermodynamically characterized binding landscape for Vav2 SH2 across EphA2 JM phosphostates, establishing quantitative recruitment rules rather than qualitative associations. The data will resolve whether Y588 and Y594 act additively or cooperatively and whether different phosphostates imply distinct binding modes or dynamic behaviors. At minimum, residuelevel interface maps from NMR will anchor mechanistic interpretation. Ideally, an atomic structure of a Vav2 SH2\u2013phosphopeptide complex will provide a highresolution reference. Together, these outcomes will supply a concrete framework for interpreting which EphA2 architectures identified in Aim\u202f1 are competent for Vav2 engagement and why. Potential pitfalls and alternative strategies If binding affinities fall outside the optimal sensitivity range for ITC, highersensitivity kinetic methods such as SPR or BLI will be emphasized, and buffer conditions will be optimized to reduce nonspecific heat contributions. If peptide context proves insufficient to capture specificity, peptide length will be expanded or additional JM residues incorporated. Alternatively, a minimal JMcontaining EphA2 intracellular fragment will be tested to capture contextdependent contributions. Should NMR spectral quality limit residuelevel mapping, construct boundaries, salt concentration, and temperature will be optimized, and selective labeling strategies will be employed as needed. If crystallography is not tractable, NMR mapping combined with quantitative binding will serve as the primary structural deliverable, with crystallography remaining opportunistic rather than gating. Integration with Aim\u202f1 Aim\u202f1 defines where the JM region is positioned within the fulllength receptor and how EphA2 organization changes upon ligand engagement, whereas Aim\u202f2 defines what the JM region does biophysically when phosphorylated. Integration will proceed through explicit, testable mapping rather than narrative linkage. Structural models from Aim\u202f1 will be used to evaluate whether the JM segment is plausibly solventexposed and accessible to the Vav2 SH2 domain in each architectural state. If Aim\u202f1 reveals ligandbiased assemblies with distinct kinase proximities or JM ordering, the quantitative binding data from Aim\u202f2 will provide the basis for arguing which assemblies are most compatible with robust Vav2 recruitment. By combining measured affinities and stoichiometries, NMRdefined binding surfaces, and spatial constraints from cryoEM, this aim will enable a mechanistic synthesis describing how EphA2 toggles between signaling outputs through coordinated phosphorylation patterning and receptor organization. Rigor and reproducibility Across both aims, the experimental design emphasizes reproducibility through independent validation, conservative interpretation, and transparent documentation.  For Aim\u202f1, construct identity and integrity will be verified by sequence confirmation and biochemical characterization prior to cryoEM analysis. Sample homogeneity will be assessed by sizeexclusion chromatography and negativestain EM before highresolution data collection, ensuring that only wellbehaved preparations advance. Key cryoEM parameters, including proteintonanodisc ratios, lipid composition, ligand valency, grid type, and blotting conditions, will be documented in detail to enable exact replication. Where feasible, independent datasets will be collected from separate protein preparations to confirm that observed architectures are not batchspecific. Image processing will be performed using multiple parameterizations to ensure that major conclusions, such as domain organization and oligomeric classes, are robust to analysis choices. Atomic modeling will be restricted to regions supported by density, and flexible or poorly resolved segments will be interpreted conservatively. For Aim\u202f2, rigor will be ensured through quantitative replication and orthogonal validation. Binding measurements will include appropriate negative controls, strict buffer matching, and accurate concentration determination, as stoichiometry and thermodynamic parameters are sensitive to these variables. Key interactions will be measured in independent replicates, ideally across multiple protein preparations, and reported with appropriate measures of variability. Trends observed by ITC will be crossvalidated using kinetic methods and thermal stability assays to guard against methodspecific artifacts. NMR titrations will be repeated at critical points to confirm that perturbation patterns are stable and not driven by sample degradation or aggregation. Structural observations from Aim\u202f1 and binding data from Aim\u202f2 will be combined to generate mechanistic models with clearly defined confidence levels, distinguishing highconfidence conclusions from hypothesisgenerating interpretations. Raw and processed datasets, including cryoEM maps, particle stacks, ITC thermograms, and NMR processing parameters, will be archived to ensure transparency and reproducibility. Together, these practices ensure that conclusions drawn from this work are robust, mechanistically grounded, and reproducible across experimental platforms.     Overall Training Goals My career goal is to become a membrane protein structural biologist in the pharmaceutical industry, developing structure-based therapeutics targeting receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs). Current RTK drugs invariably fail due to resistance because we lack atomic-resolution structures of full-length receptors in their membrane environment, forcing drug design to rely on incomplete structural information from isolated domains. My research focuses on EphA2, an RTK overexpressed in 40% of breast cancers and 90% of glioblastomas. While individual EphA2 domains have been crystallized, the full-length receptor remains structurally uncharacterized due to its size (>100 kDa), membrane-spanning architecture, and conformational flexibility. Recent advances in cryoEM and nanodisc technology now make these structures achievable. By systematically optimizing expression constructs, screening lipid compositions, and developing novel grid preparation protocols, I will capture EphA2 in multiple functional states\u2014revealing how cancer cells hijack its signaling and exposing new drug targets at domain interfaces. My diverse research background\u2014from computational pattern recognition to molecular biology\u2014taught me that breakthrough solutions often come from approaching problems differently. Where others see EphA2's complexity as a barrier, I see an intricate system waiting to be understood through systematic optimization. This F31 training will transform my interdisciplinary perspective into the specialized expertise needed to solve structures that could fundamentally change RTK-targeted therapies. Professional Development Goal Cross-disciplinary Team Leadership: I lack formal training in leading interdisciplinary scientific teams. Purdue's Project Management Certificate will teach me to manage complex R&D timelines and communicate technical milestones to non-specialists. Co-leading our lab's collaboration with medicinal chemistry and participating in the Entrepreneurship Academy will prepare me to bridge academic discovery and industry development. Quantitative Skills Goal Computer-aided Drug Design: MCMP 690 will provide foundational skills in molecular docking, interaction mapping, and virtual screening, tools I need to translate structures into drug leads. While one course won't make me an expert, it will enable effective collaboration with computational chemists. Technical Goals CryoEM Expertise: Through systematic training on Purdue's Titan Krios, I'll master particle classification and 3D variability analysis to capture EphA2's conformational states. Even capturing two distinct states would significantly advance current knowledge. Biophysical Characterization: I'll develop proficiency in ITC, SPR, and DSF to validate that structural states represent functional conformations, bridging the gap between structures and pharmaceutical relevance. Membrane Mimetic Systems: I'll master nanodisc technology and explore SMALPs to maintain EphA2's native lipid interactions throughout structural studies. These integrated goals address pharmaceutical industry requirements: computational skills to identify drug targets, biophysical validation of functional relevance, and leadership training to guide interdisciplinary teams from structure to lead compound. Candidate's Preparedness My path to membrane protein structural biology represents strategic skill accumulation building toward tackling full-length EphA2. Each experience deliberately built capabilities I now deploy in pursuit of structures that have eluded the field for decades. Foundation in Computational and Systems Analysis My research journey began with bioinformatics under Dr. Ellen Pritham at UT Arlington, where I traced horizontal gene transfer events between distantly related species. This work required more than running Basic Local Alignment Search Tool (BLAST) searches, I had to understand how transposable element sequences evolved, recognize degraded motifs, and predict functional consequences of insertions near regulatory regions. Using MEME for motif discovery and ClustalW for alignment optimization, I learned to identify patterns invisible to cursory analysis. This training proves essential now as I design EphA2 constructs, ensuring my truncations preserve functional motifs while removing disordered regions that impede crystallization. When I discovered certain EphA2 mutations cluster in regions controlling oligomerization rather than kinase activity, my training allowed me to recognize this as evidence of selection pressure, cancer cells specifically targeting regulatory mechanisms. At Argonne National Laboratory with Dr. Uisung Lee, I conducted comprehensive life-cycle analysis of polylactic acid, tracking energy and material flows across 50+ interconnected variables.  I had to understand how upstream changes propagated through the entire system, optimize multiple parameters simultaneously, and validate my model against real-world data. My work, now incorporated into the GREET\u00ae 2019 model used by researchers worldwide, required the same systematic thinking I apply to membrane protein purification. When optimizing EphA2 expression, I similarly track how changes in induction temperature affect not just yield but also protein folding, post-translational modifications, and ultimately structural homogeneity. This systems-level perspective helped me recognize that EphA2's tendency to aggregate wasn't a simple concentration effect but resulted from specific lipid depletion during purification, a connection I might have missed without my environmental analysis background. Molecular Biology and Technical Innovation My Master's research on Tonneau1 Recruiting Motif (TRM) proteins under Dr. Viktor Kirik provided essential molecular biology training. Using live-cell confocal microscopy, I tracked fluorescently-tagged TRM18 in plant cells, systematically creating deletion constructs to map functional domains through phenotypic analysis. This work taught me how removing or altering specific protein regions affects cellular localization and function. This is directly relevant to designing EphA2 constructs that maintain native behavior while being amenable to structural studies. My improvement to Gateway cloning (a method for moving DNA between plasmids), published in BioTechniques, streamlined the creation of these numerous constructs. By developing polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-based approaches that joined DNA fragments without expensive enzymes, I reduced costs by 70% while increasing cloning success rates. This same systematic approach to optimization now drives my membrane protein work. Current Specialization in Membrane Protein Structural Biology In Dr. Stauffacher's lab, I've transitioned from broad molecular biology to focused structural approaches. Initial attempts to crystallize EphA2's kinase domain taught me valuable lessons about construct design, protein stability, and the importance of post-translational modifications. When crystals diffracting to only 8\u00c5 revealed aggregation issues, I didn't simply try more conditions, I stepped back to understand why this well-behaved domain in solution became problematic in crystals. This led to my current approach using full-length protein in nanodiscs, preserving native oligomerization interfaces. My technical preparation now includes advanced coursework in macromolecular crystallography, where I learned to optimize crystallization strategies for challenging targets; biophysical methods, providing quantitative frameworks for validating protein functionality; and currently, comprehensive cryoEM training on Purdue's Titan Krios. I've spent countless hours studying grid optimization, learning that success requires understanding not just the microscope but also how proteins behave at air-water interfaces. Through the Purdue cryoEM facility, I'm gaining hands-on experience with every step from sample prep through data processing in RELION and cryoSPARC. This combination of computational pattern recognition, systematic optimization, and molecular biology creates a unique lens for approaching membrane protein challenges. Where traditional structural biologists might focus solely on crystallization conditions, my bioinformatics training alerts me to conserved motifs that must be preserved in constructs. My systems-level thinking from environmental modeling helps me recognize how seemingly unrelated variables (temperature, lipid composition, buffer pH) interact to affect protein stability. The iterative optimization skills honed through Gateway cloning improvements transfer directly to the patient, methodical screening required for membrane protein success. Most importantly, my cross-disciplinary path taught me that breakthroughs often come from applying insights from unexpected sources. This convergence of skills from multiple fields positions me to see solutions that single-discipline training might miss. Candidate's Self-Assessment Current Strengths Systems-Level Thinking My diverse research background enables me to recognize how interconnected variables affect protein behavior, from understanding transposon evolution patterns to optimizing multi-parameter environmental models, I approach EphA2 as a complex system rather than isolated technical challenges. Technical Innovation I consistently identify and improve inefficient processes, evidenced by my Gateway cloning optimization (70% cost reduction) and recognizing that full-length EphA2 in nanodiscs could succeed where isolated domain crystallization failed. Cross-Disciplinary Pattern Recognition Years of jumping between fields trained me to apply insights from unexpected sources, like using environmental chemistry principles to solve membrane protein lipid requirements. Areas for Development Advanced CryoEM Data Processing I aim to build expertise in particle classification and conformational heterogeneity analysis by attending advanced cryoEM workshops at leading centers such as SEMC a