 hope to reveal how ligand binding controls kinase activation across the full receptor. These structures could expose previously hidden drug-binding sites at domain interfaces, potentially enabling design of allosteric modulators that restore tumor-suppressive function. While ambitious, even partial success (capturing EphA2 in two functionally distinct states) would significantly advance our understanding of RTK regulation and open new therapeutic avenues.   Training Activities and Timeline Key Training Personnel and Collaborators My training will be guided by the following mentors and collaborators: Primary Sponsor  Dr. Cynthia Stauffacher, Professor and Associate Head for Research and Graduate Education, Department of Biological Sciences, Purdue University. Specialization: X-ray crystallography of macromolecular systems including membrane-associated proteins, ABC-transporters, and protein tyrosine phosphatases. Role: Primary mentor providing daily guidance on construct design, structural biology techniques, and career development through weekly one-on-one meetings. Her experience with NIH study sections and Cancer Institute site visits provides valuable grant-writing guidance. Committee Members Dr. Carol Post, Distinguished Professor of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Borch Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Purdue University. Specialization: Computational analysis of protein dynamics and conformational ensembles using molecular dynamics simulations. Role: Guides computational approaches to analyzing EphA2 conformational heterogeneity from cryoEM data. Dr. Robert Stahelin, Retter Professor of Pharmacy and Professor of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Borch Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Purdue University. Specialization: Lipid-protein interactions and membrane biophysics. Role: Provides ITC training and expertise in phospholipid-dependent protein behavior, crucial for nanodisc optimization. Dr. John Tesmer, Walther Distinguished Professor in Cancer Structural Biology, Department of Biological Sciences, Purdue University. Specialization: GPCR structure and signaling, protein phosphorylation mechanisms. Role: Provides expertise in analyzing phosphorylation-dependent conformational changes and receptor activation mechanisms, critical for understanding EphA2's transition between tumor-suppressive and oncogenic states. Collaborative Development Process This training plan emerged through discussions with my sponsor Dr. Stauffacher during our weekly meetings, where we've refined both research strategy and professional development goals. Her experience with challenging protein structures guided my pivot from crystallography attempts to exploring cryoEM approaches for full-length EphA2. My committee members provide complementary expertise that will shape my training. Dr. Tesmer's knowledge of receptor phosphorylation mechanisms will guide my approach to capturing phosphorylation-dependent conformational states. Dr. Post's computational expertise will help me analyze conformational heterogeneity in future cryoEM datasets. Dr. Stahelin has already provided hands-on ITC training through his graduate student, giving me foundational skills in thermodynamic analysis that I'll expand throughout my training. The specific training activities outlined below leverage Purdue's research infrastructure and my committee's connections. As I progress from foundational techniques to advanced applications, this plan will adapt based on preliminary results and evolving opportunities. Regular committee meetings will ensure my training remains aligned with both project needs and career goals. Year 1 (Current Year): Foundation Building This year establishes core technical competencies while beginning professional skill development. Research focuses on solving the fundamental challenge of obtaining stable, monodisperse EphA2 in nanodiscs. I will be expressing full-length EphA2 in insect cells and optimizing purification protocols. I'll apply docking simulations to predict how sterile alpha motif (SAM) domain positioning might create allosteric pockets. Dr. Robert Stahelin (Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology) provides ITC training as I validate ligand binding in different phosphomutants."
