s, I hope to reveal how ligand binding controls kinase activation across the full receptor. These structures could expose previously hidden drug-binding sites at domain interfaces, potentially enabling design of allosteric modulators that restore tumor-suppressive function. While ambitious, even partial success (capturing EphA2 in two functionally distinct states) would significantly advance our understanding of RTK regulation and open new therapeutic avenues.   Training Activities and Timeline Key Training Personnel and Collaborators My training will be guided by the following mentors and collaborators: Primary Sponsor  Dr. Cynthia Stauffacher, Professor and Associate Head for Research and Graduate Education, Department of Biological Sciences, Purdue University. Specialization: X-ray crystallography of macromolecular systems including membrane-associated proteins, ABC-transporters, and protein tyrosine phosphatases. Role: Primary mentor providing daily guidance on construct design, structural biology techniques, and career development through weekly one-on-one meetings. Her experience with NIH study sections and Cancer Institute site visits provides valuable grant-writing guidance. Committee Members Dr. Carol Post, Distinguished Professor of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Borch Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Purdue University. Specialization: Computational analysis of protein dynamics and conformational ensembles using molecular dynamics simulations. Role: Guides computational approaches to analyzing EphA2 conformational heterogeneity from cryoEM data. Dr. Robert Stahelin, Retter Professor of Pharmacy and Professor of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Borch Department of Medicinal Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Purdue University. Specialization: Lipid-protein interactions and membrane biophysics. Role: Provides ITC training and expertise in phospholipid-dependent protein behavior, crucial for nano