            "Risk Mitigation and Alternative Approaches I recognize membrane protein structural biology's inherent unpredictability. If full-length EphA2 proves intractable, I'll pursue systematic domain combinations (kinase+transmembrane, then add SAM) to identify minimal constructs capturing oligomerization interfaces. If cryoEM resolution stalls above 4\u00c5, I'll pivot to capturing larger conformational changes that remain informative at lower resolution. Even 6\u00c5 structures showing domain rearrangements would advance the field. Should specific phosphomutants fail to stabilize distinct states, I'll screen small molecules known to bias EphA2 signaling as conformational tools. If planned internships don't materialize, I'll pursue extended collaborations with Eli Lilly (Indianapolis, 60 miles away) enabling regular visits while maintaining dissertation progress. These contingencies ensure productive training regardless of technical challenges. Transition to Next Career Stage This comprehensive training will prepare me for senior scientist positions in pharmaceutical structural biology. The combination of membrane protein expertise, cryoEM proficiency, and drug discovery experience will match current industry needs. My publications will demonstrate both technical excellence and translational applications and will establish credibility. The internship will provide networking and cultural understanding crucial for successful integration into industry. Additionally, my non-traditional background adds valuable perspective on persistence, resource optimization, and creative problem-solving. Research Environment Suitability Purdue provides ideal training through world-class facilities, collaborative culture, and strong industry connections. The cryoEM facility's Titan Krios will enable cutting-edge structural studies. Integration with drug discovery cores will facilitate translational applications. Dr. Stauffacher's mentorship record, with former students in leadership at leading biotech companies, demonstrates training effectiveness. This environment, combined with my determination and unique perspective, will ensure successful preparation for industry leadership. Success Metrics and Evaluation Progress will be evaluated through concrete milestones: Year 1: achieve reproducible EphA2 expression >2mg/L and monodisperse nanodisc samples; Year 2: obtain 3.5\u00c5 or better cryoEM structure with clear density for all domains; Year 3: validate at least 3 fragment hits with a dissociation constant (KD) <100\u03bcM; Year 4: publish 2+ high-impact papers and secure industry position. Annual committee reviews assess both technical progress and professional development, adjusting the plan as needed.  References 1)\tNigro, E, Imperlini, E. Scudiero, O, Monaco, ML, Polito, R, Mazzarella, G. Orru, S, Bianco, A, Daniele, A. Differentially expressed and activated proteins associated with non small cell lung cancer tissues. Respiratory Research. 2015; 16:74 2)\tBrannan, JM, Sen, B, Saigal, B, Prudkin, L, Behrens, C, Solis, L, Dong, W, Bekele, BN, Wistuba, I, Johnson, FM. EphA2 in the early pathogenesis of progression of non-small cell lung cancer. Cancer Prev Res. 2009; 2(12):1039-1049 3)\tGe, L, Wu, B, Zhang, Y, Wang, J, Zhao, H, Wang, J. Biochemical and NMR characterization of the interactions of Vav2-SH2 domain with lipids and the EphA2 juxtamembrane region on membrane. Biochemical Journal. 2020; 444: 3791-3801 4)\tXiao, T, Xiao, Y, Wang, W, Tang, YY, Xiao, Z, Su, M. Targeting EphA2 in cancer. Journal of Hematology & Oncology. 2020; 13:114 5)\tGuo, X, Yang, Y, Tang, J, Xiang, J. Ephs in cancer progression: complexity and context-dependent nature in signaling, angiogenesis and immunity. Cell Communication and Signaling. 2024; 22:299 6)\tHornstein, I, Alcover, A, Katzav, S. Vav proteins, masters of the world of cytoskeleton organization. Cellular Signaling. 2004; 16:1-11 7)\tLondon, M, Gallo, E. The EphA2 and cancer connection: potential for